Creating the Participant Summaries in R

Background on the WorkAndHome project

As part of the WorkAndHome project we are conducting a large GPS-based mobile app survey. Within this survey we are monitoring the movement of over 800 participants using GPS tracking, and systematically sampling their experiences throughout the day using a mobile-survey platform. The mobile application we are using was developed by Wubbleyou and the participant recruitment was conducted by BMG Research.

Need for an Infographic

As part of our mobile survey we want to report back to our participants that is to share the data we have collected about them with them, after they have finished their participation. We needed to identify people from our much larger dataset using their Participant ID, and then produce a summary of their particpation via the data.

To do so we wanted to create an anonymous and automated piece of R analysis that produced a production quality graphic that summarizes their data. To our surprise their were few examples of this type of output on R, despite the fact that combining multiple plots, graphics, and text on a single figure is well documented in the R infrastructure. We did however find one nice example and we chose to build on the ideas that were used in that blogpost.

Infographic Components

Our survey consisted of two seperate but related datasets:

I. GPS tracking data II. Survey question responses

Therefore, we wanted the infographic to show:

  1. Summary statistics about the particpant and their data;
  2. Maps of participant GPS tracking data, overlaid on a basemap/satellite imagery;
  3. Frequency histograms of responses from three different survey qeustions about feelings;
  4. Tables of the top responses from three different survey questions activities;
  5. Logos and information about the study.

Building individual Componenets

First we started by building three separate maps of the users GPS tracking data:

  • one showing their entire track;
  • one centered on their home;
  • one cenetered on their work or other top location.

We used the ggmap package to create the maps and used the Google satellite imagery as the underlying basemap (requiring us to have an Google Static Maps API key).

We then produced three histograms (in ggplot2) based on the participant survey responses about how they feel at different times throughout the survey.

Finally, we generated tabular data and created table objects using the tableGrob function in the gridExtra package.

The infographic layout, including text additions, was fully implemented using the grid-graphics package. Specifically, we used this package for everything from:

  • creating background colours
  • all text
  • placing figures
  • reading and plotting logos

An example of the data we collected is provided on our project GitHub page (this is Jeds data from when we were testing the App). There are two files, one for the location data and one for the survey data.

We created a create_infographic function, which we used to automate the process of creating summary reports for our 800+ participants. The R code for the create_infographic function can be found here on our github page. An example of our finished product is below!
